<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1445,2009]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,468,1697,1722]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Immediately differentiated from other members of the 
<emphasis box="[1102,1205,1697,1721]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Velvetina</emphasis>
group by the dorsal color, the comparatively wide pronotum having a piceous fascia bordered by testaceous bands in front and back (color band ratios ca. 5/15/4) (
<figureCitation box="[489,587,1769,1793]" captionStart="FIGURE 106" captionStartId="224.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[222,1371,203,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-29@224.[201,1385,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="224" captionText="FIGURE 106. Hydraena velvetina, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283622" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283622/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 106</figureCitation>
). In addition, the elytra, when viewed posteriorly, do not form an angle with one another. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[482,617,1805,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velvetina">
<emphasis box="[482,502,1806,1829]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[516,617,1805,1829]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">velvetina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is perhaps best compared with that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[1044,1162,1805,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bubulla">
<emphasis box="[1044,1064,1806,1829]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1077,1162,1805,1829]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">bubulla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1178,1285,1805,1829]" captionStart="FIGURES 108–109" captionStartId="226.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[297,1324,198,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-32@226.[226,1360,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="226" captionText="FIGURES 108–109. Aedeagi of holotypes. 108. H. velvetina. 109. H. ibalimi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283626" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283626/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Figs. 108</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1296,1340,1805,1829]" captionStart="FIGURES 112–113" captionStartId="229.[151,263,1650,1673]" captionText="FIGURES 112–113. Aedeagi of holotypes. 112. H. adelbertensis. 113. H. bubulla." pageId="66" pageNumber="67">113</figureCitation>
), but the two differ markedly in many ways, and externally the two species are quite distinct (
<figureCitation box="[1097,1204,1841,1865]" captionStart="FIGURE 106" captionStartId="224.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[222,1371,203,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-29@224.[201,1385,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="224" captionText="FIGURE 106. Hydraena velvetina, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283622" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283622/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Figs. 106</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1216,1260,1841,1865]" captionStart="FIGURE 111" captionStartId="228.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[256,1331,193,1732]" captionTargetId="figure-29@228.[256,1331,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="228" captionText="FIGURE 111. Hydraena bubulla, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283636" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283636/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">111</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
